text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Expansion: ASL acquisition%0a:Author: meng_s%0a:Original: [[Articles.ASLAndMedicine|ASLAndMedicine]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.VikramM|VikramM]]%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 07.05.2021 - 20:59%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-223448-420300#%0a* [-11.05.2021 - 15:34-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-223448-420300#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aApart from the lack of healthcare professionals fluent in ASL and/or ASL translators, another barrier to ASL acquisition is the stance that deafness is a condition to be treated. In this article, it was mentioned that the mission of the Alexander Graham Bell Association for the Deaf and Hard of Hearing (AGB) is to “[help] families, health care providers and education professionals understand childhood hearing loss and the importance of early diagnosis and intervention”. Such a stance perpetuates the idea that a Deaf child cannot lead a fulfilling life and assumes that Deaf people are desperate to be part of the hearing world. However, we can tell from the protests against the Listening and Spoken Language Symposium organized by AGB led by Deaf people mentioned in the article that this is far from the truth. ASL is important to many in the Deaf community and oralist methods, such as cochlear implants, oral speech and lip reading, treats ASL as inferior to spoken languages. It is important to promote ASL acquisition among deaf children rather than impose oralist methods on them.%0ahttps://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2013/08/understanding-deafness-not-everyone-wants-to-be-fixed/278527/%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a: